2 traditional hinges in Pilates and a variation: we have “the Hinge” and the “Hip Hinge”
“The hinge” is a fantastic exercise to strengthen your quads and reinforce the knees while learning how to actively contract abs and flutes to maintain a straight and natural spine alignment. 
The hinge variation with the twist increases its difficulty and stimulates obliques and transversus while forces your hip to maintain neutrality. 
The “hip hinge” works balance, core control and a basic movement pattern that is hip flexion/extension, strengthening the ileo-psoas, the rectus femoris, sartorius, the tensor fascia lata and a small muscle in your groin called “pectineus”

The thoracic spine (upper back region) is an important section of the spine that often loses mobility in populations that are more sedentary.

The thoracic spine is meant to flex, extend and rotate. 

If the thoracic spine is immobile, the lumbar spine will pick up the slack and compensate. This can lead to low back pain and fatigue.
This can also cause problems in the shoulders and neck.

Benefits of Thoracic Spine Mobility
* A healthier kyphosis (natural curve of the thoracic area)
* Healthier shoulders
* Reduced neck and low back pain
* Increased lung volume
* Decreased risk of injuries
* Improved chest-back balance
